What is really fascinating is the antigenic imprinting hypothesis - so natural immunity to future variants could depend on which variant your system encountered first - and perhaps which vaccine?

snippet.textDisplay:
Since the outbreak the virus has drifted from original form to Alpha, Beta ,  Gamma and the dominant Delta strain
So far the talk is about immunity gain after recovery from particular strain but not of the later and other mutated strain.
1. Scientist does not know if recovered patient from say alpha variant could well be infected with the delta variant within a short span of time.
2. As the virus mutates (drifted) further away from the original version, the immunity gain from existing vaccine may no longer be effective. 
3. However, many expert claim that the vaccine is still effective as it reduces the severity of the disease and reduce mortality. 

4. Could the explanation in 3 , turn vaccinated person into a carriers especially the Delta variant? That could explain why with the ramp up of the vaccination in many nation, the world is seeing a rise in the delta variant , instead of a decline. Has anybody thought about this possibility that the combination of mass vaccination and the delta variant be responsible for the global rise of the delta variant?  
Since the vaccine reduce severity, some vaccinated person may be asymptomatic or exhibit delayed symptom and unwittingly infect others!
The virus has proven to be formidable. Perhaps we need 3 doses of the vaccine or even a more powerful vaccine to combat the mutated form.

snippet.textDisplay:
Technically there is just one strain of SARS-CoV-2 with over two million registered variants (genomic sequences) but just a dozen or so of the variants are of interest or concern.  Sometimes the nomenclature “strain” is used to mean a family or branch of virus variants coming from a common ancestor but this should be called a “clade”.  Sometimes “strain” is used to mean one of eight lineages or some sub-lineage, but there are actually high-level clades.  Strain is open to different interpretations but it usually means a virus variant that has some very different properties, which entails a subjective opinion.  Strictly speaking, a variant becomes a strain when it has a demonstrably different phenotype (e.g., a difference in antigenicity, transmissibility, or virulence).

A rule of thumb is that variants all respond to the same vaccine (perhaps with different speeds or efficacy) but different strains usually need different vaccines to have serious stopping power.  Some experts are arguing that the Delta variant has already evolved into a new strain, SARS-CoV-3 maybe.  The Delta variant is likely in a gray area between the two arguments so 3 doses of an existing vaccine should still stop this variant (i.e. prevent any symptoms).  But it is not yet a new strain.

I don’t think a third dose is warranted for the vast majority of people (yet).  Vaccinated people can handle a week of sniffles and many unvaccinated people in some places are still waiting for a first dose.  The Delta variant is more transmissible (including from and to people with some immunity) but likely it is not more deadly on a single case basis.  And possibly even less deadly since it tends to stay in the upper respiratory tract where it can spread to others more easily but where it causes less lung and other vital organ damage (but the younger age groups being infected with it may be a factor here).  The good news is a more transmissible virus will end the pandemic sooner, but at a huge price.

There’s a saying that what doesn’t kill you makes you stronger.  It certainly applies to microbes with all the antibiotic-resistant versions of bacteria arising.  Antigenic drift and antigenic shift continually give rise to new variants but most of these variants just disappear.  Strong natural selection among competing viruses leaves just the fittest to spread.  Suppressing the Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Epsilon, Zeta, Eta, Theta, Iota, Kappa and Lambda variants with vaccines has left the field wide open to one variant that knows how to evade antibodies a bit better than all the others – that’s the Delta variant.  The Delta variant arose in India before vaccines were a consideration (it was detected in October 2020) and it remained secondary to the Alpha variant until after the huge May 2021 wave in India when many people acquired some natural immunity.  As people acquired immunity, the advantage of the Delta variant could be put to use.  Keep an eye on Delta Plus too—it’s a subvariant of Delta — it likes lung cells.

In any case, SARS-CoV-2 is just an Influenza-like virus temporarily on steroids.  Remember the Spanish Flu?  This pandemic will pass soon and it will be largely forgotten in ten years.

snippet.textDisplay: Again it seems that the specialist is perhaps conflating infection with symptoms. AFAIK, at least originally, what was assessed in terms of "efficacy" was efficacy in preventing symptoms, not infection. You'd have something like 95% of people who didn't require an ICU or any hospitalization, but who could have had moderate and mild disease, the milder, the more common. And even those who had no symptom whatsoever could still have had a completely asymptomatic infection, just like what happens with the non-vaccinated at some significant fraction of the time. AFAIK the prevention of infection itself (and potential transmission) was (or is currently being) only inferred more indirectly, with fewer new cases on the houses of people where someone was vaccinated and so forth. But even there perhaps there can be cases of new asymptomatic infections, with vaccinated people transmitting at lower doses and more likely causing asymptomatic infections at this level.

snippet.textDisplay:
​@Böser.Stachel the question of antibodies is a bit ambiguous. Our immune system has several layers and antibodies are just one part of it. They mostly die off after a certain period of time if there is no infection. However, memory cells which are also part of our immune bodies store information about each pathogen they encounter. Once they "see" it again, they send a chemical signal to the rest of the immune system which begins to produce necessary antibodies to combat that specific pathogen. So antibodies do disappear with time, but it does not mean that our bodies are unprepared for a subsequent infection by the same pathogen. 



With influenza viruses, the problem is that they mutate too quickly to the point where our bodies stop recognising them, but you remain virtually immune to the same strain. There is a certain concern that SARS-Cov-2 might turn into a rapidly mutating virus, just like influenza viruses are. If it happens, we will likely need vaccine shots each time a new strain appears as it currently happens with the flu.
